title: Grampians NP - Plants
description: There are more than 1000 species of wildflowers, many of which are commonly seen.

items.title: Bossiaea cinerea
items.content_text: From the shape of the leaves it looks like bossiaea cinerea.

items.title: Ozothamnus obcordatus
items.content_text: Location approximate, between Splitters Falls and Wonderland Car Park.

items.title: Correa aemula
items.content_text: Location approximate. Between Splitters Falls and Wonderland Car Park.

items.title: Leionema bilobum subsp. bilobum

items.title: Corunastylis morrisii
items.content_text: Only three plants found in this area - this is the most advanced in flower. Other two had very juvenile buds.

items.title: Euryomyrtus ramosissima subsp. prostrata
items.content_text: Tiny prostate plant with tiny flowers (about 7-8mm diam) which face downwards. Woody stem. Observed Sept to Nov.

items.title: Daviesia arenaria
items.content_text: Daviesia arenaria because of the colour of the flower and the ‘folded’ phyllodes.

items.title: Utricularia tenella
items.content_text: Annual terrestrial with very small leaves

items.title: Lindsaea linearis
items.content_text: in damp sand in area burnt several months ago

items.title: Dillwynia hispida
items.content_text: Single plant in remnant red gum grasslands

items.title: Acacia aculeatissima
items.content_text: stunted plants - clearly eaten by something - 15cm X 30cm. Unusual red centres to flowers on one plant. About 80 metres west of the crest of the gap on the roadside.

items.title: Hibbertia humifusa
items.content_text: in sand - 25cm. Not sure of subspecies?

items.title: Ixodia achillaeoides subsp. alata
items.content_text: vast numbers of these plants mostly finished flowering in previously burnt area

items.title: Pterostylis sanguinea
items.content_text: small colony this was the largest about 40cm tall

items.title: Acacia farinosa
items.content_text: Described by Neil Marriott as Acacia sp. aff. farinosa - growing in seasonally wet clay. Low spreading shrub to 1 metre. 3 metres wide.

items.title: Cyphanthera anthocercidea
items.content_text: Recolonising prolifically following January 2014 bushfire of the northern Grampians.

items.title: Scaevola aemula
items.content_text: Growing at base of cliff of Back Wall at Hollow Mountain. Procumbent shrub.

items.title: Ixodia achillaeoides subsp. alata
items.content_text: Recolonising prolifically following January 2014 bushfire of the northern Grampians.

items.title: Asplenium flabellifolium
items.content_text: Growing from rock crevice (Back Wall of Hollow Mountain), approx. 2m from ground.

items.title: Solanum spp.
items.content_text: Plants to 2.5m tall, producing green berries that appear to turn yellow with age. Leaves predominately non-lobed, narrowly lanceolate (linear-lanceolate) to 10cm long.

items.title: Lasiopetalum macrophyllum
items.content_text: Regenerating plants following the January 2004 bushfire of the northern Grampians.

items.title: Acacia gunnii
items.content_text: small plant 30cm. Very interesting pinky tinge to flowers!

items.title: Calandrinia eremaea
items.content_text: Plant with pink globular leaves growing on top of moss. Location approximate, on the walking path toward Mt Zero lookout.

items.title: Burnettia cuneata
items.content_text: These orchids flowered after the 2006 summer wildfires.

items.title: Correa reflexa var. angustifolia
items.content_text: Can just make out what looks like 8 tiny lobes on calyx.

items.title: Correa reflexa var. angustifolia
items.content_text: Could be var. angustifolia? Leaves have an unusually high length:width ratio.

items.title: Allocasuarina grampiana
items.content_text: 1m shrub exposed site on sandstone at Mt William.

items.title: Eucalyptus serraensis
items.content_text: Small tree about 3.5m tall on exposed site at Mt William. Fruit slightly warty. Looks to be Eucalyptus serraensis by its location. Smooth trunk but tree still small. Thick leaves.

items.title: Monotoca scoparia
items.content_text: Female flowers and immature fruit on Monotoca scoparia

items.title: Pelargonium australe
items.content_text: Thousands of plants flowering en-masse after January fires.

items.title: Unidentified
items.content_text: Unknown at this stage. One plant growing  on a rock face.

items.title: Conospermum mitchellii
items.content_text: Appears to be moth eggs (?) placed neatly on the leaves.

items.title: Caladenia alpina
items.content_text: I think attempts have been made to change the name of this Grampians entity to C. lyallii - see ALA. PlantNet and VBA say C. lyallii = C. alpina.

items.title: Leucopogon thymifolius
items.content_text: Mt William form - see Flora of Victoria.

items.title: Stylidium soboliferum
items.content_text: Lots in bud but only one plant with flowers remotely visible.

items.title: Dianella admixta
items.content_text: Very black anthers and black stripe on back of tepals.

items.title: Pultenaea mollis
items.content_text: Note very hairy stem at top of photo

items.title: Leporella fimbriata
items.content_text:
Flowers in Autumn (Apr - Jun), favours heathland and woodland with heath under-story usually in sandy soil.
This species often grows in large colonies and flowers prolifically only after fire.
This form is very unusual.

items.title: Acacia oxycedrus
items.content_text: Shrub about 2m high and wide Wonderland track Grampians

items.title: Correa aemula x reflexa
items.content_text: Small shrub 05m tall sparse flowers. Hairy leaves and features of Correa aemula but colour of Correa reflexa.

items.title: Asplenium flabellifolium
items.content_text: In crevices between rocks on the Wonderland Walk Grampians NP

items.title: Acacia stricta
items.content_text: Shrubs to about 1.5m on sandstone outcrops in Wonderland walk Grampians

items.title: Hibbertia cistiflora subsp. rostrata
items.content_text: Shrub about 0.8m tall 1m wide on Wonderland track.

items.title: Thelymitra matthewsii
items.content_text:
Flowers in Spring (Sep), favours poor gravelly soil, mainly coastal, often in areas that have been disturbed.
The flower is temperamental and reluctant to open unless circumstances are exactly right.

items.title: Correa aemula
items.content_text: Very pale flowers for Correa aemula you can see how hairy the plant is close up.

items.title: Leptospermum turbinatum
items.content_text: These leptospermum flowers are very large - around 4cm in diameter - the shrubs 2m tall on exposed sandstone outcrops.

items.title: Leionema bilobum subsp. bilobum
items.content_text: On the Wonderland walk in the Grampians - small shrub.
